of Norse myths and poems."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Foel\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, composed of two different Hebrew elements, <i>Yah(weh)</i> and <i>El</i>, both of which mean ‘God’ the implication of the name is that the Hebrew God, <i>Yahweh</i>, is the only true god. This is a common name in the Bible, being borne by, among others, one of King David's ‘mighty men’ (1 Chronicles 11:38), and a minor prophet who lived in the 8th century  bc . The name has been perennially popular as a Jewish name; it was also taken up by the Puritans and other Christian fundamentalists. The name has long been in regular use in North America but was uncommon in Britain until the 1990s. Well-known bearers of the name include the American singer and entertainer  Joel Grey  (  b. 1932 ), the West Indian cricketer  Joel Garner  (  b. 1952 ), and the American film director  Joel Coen  (  b. 1954 ). The French form  <b>Joël</b>  is also used in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Adda \" Foel\" ap Einion was born about 1280, in Rhoscolyn, Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Einion \" Felyn\" ap Adda. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs. Adda ap Enion. He died after 1352."},"et":{"ABT    1280–AFT    1352":"umbes 1280–pärast 1352","1280–1352":"1280–1352","–Female":"Surnud","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1308–Male":"1308–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1305":"1305","AFT    1352":"pärast 1352","about 1305":"umbes 1305","1352":"1352","ABT    1308":"umbes 1308","1240":"1240","ABT    1280":"umbes 1280","1308":"1308","1280":"1280","Ceidio Rhodogeidio, Anglesey, Wales":"Ceidio Rhodogeidio, Anglesey, Wales","of,Rhoscolyn,Anglesey,Wales":"Rhoscolyn, Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT    1280–AFT    1352":"noin 1280–1352 jälkeen","1280–1352":"1280–1352","–Female":"Kuollut","1305–Male":"1305–Kuollut","1308–Male":"1308–Kuo